@s0undt3ch A couple of questions / comments:
1. Are you sure this is not a bad / flaky local connection or a server side issue?
2. Can you provide more environment details (Python versions, etc.) and post a code which reproduces this issue? 
3. We don't do anything nasty with threads or anything else I'm aware which could cause GIL deadlock so only thing I could see causing this is a bug in CPython which (imo) is unlikely.

@alex is way more familiar with CPython internals than I am so he might have some better ideas of what could be going on here.

@Kami I found one issue with my code, which I fixed. You can review what I have now if you like.

I was thinking for testing, without requiring any running nodes or drives, the only way to test whether the general Driver connects to the various API endpoints would be to use one region's credentials for another region when instantiating the driver, then catching the invalid credentials exception when trying to run a command with that driver.

If that sounds sufficient for you then I'll go ahead and add those in. It wouldn't require any fixtures, just a valid test.secrets file.

@s0undt3ch OK, thanks for keeping me posted. This does seem like an intermediate (networking) issue then.

Out of curiosity, do you happen to know how many requests were made during this last period?

In any case, thanks. Feel free to close the PR.

@wrigri Thanks and sorry for the delay.

We don't receive notifications when you add a comment so next time please mention my nickname so I will receive a notification and respond faster.

Anyway, please squash all the commits and attach latest patch to the JIRA ticket and I will get it merged.

@gigimon OK, in this case I would do the following:
1. Change the constructor to `def __init__(self, id, size, driver, extra=None):`
2. Store `description` and `name` (for providers which expose it) in the `extra` dictionary
